Exercise 2: Regression and model validation

Exam Success on an Introductory Social Statistics Course of 2014

The current research explores the exam success on an introductory social statistics course in 2014. The research question is: Which factors contributed to exam success on the course “Introduction to Social Statistics” in the fall of 2014?

Data

Our wrangled dataset of 166 observations is based on an international survey of Approaches to Learning concerning teaching and learning during an introductory course to social statistics conducted in the fall of 2014. The survey data were collected between 3.12.2014 - 10.1.2015 by Kimmo Vehkalahti. The seven variables here observed are gender, age, global attitude towards statistics, points acquired in exam, and altogether three varying approaches to learning: the deep, surface and strategic approach, measured on a Likert-scale of 1-5. An overview of the data is shown below in Figure 1.

# loading libraries
library(ggplot2)
library(GGally)

# importing learning2014 data
learning2014 <- read.table("http://s3.amazonaws.com/assets.datacamp.com/production/course_2218/datasets/learning2014.txt", sep=",", header=TRUE)

# summary of the data
summary(learning2014)

Figure 1. Summary and scatter matrix of the study dataset. It seems our gender distribution is quite uneven with significantly more female participants in the dataset (indicated here by the colour red). Most of our variables are quite normally distributed. The age distribution is a little downwardly skew with a couple of elderly outliers. The points distribution seems to have a small bump in the lower quartile, otherwise characterized by seemingly normal distribution. Correlations seem to be significantly positive between variables attitude and points and negative, expectedly, between variables related to surface and deep learning approaches.

Analysis

First, I will test the hypothesis, that the variable “points”, indicating the exam points of the participants, is best explained by the variables attitude, deep learning approach and strategic learning approach. I will fit a regression model to the data with these three explanatory variables.

pointsmodel <- lm(points ~ attitude + deep + stra, data = learning2014)
summary(pointsmodel)

It would here seem that the variable attitude a clear, statistically significant, positive explanatory relation with the exam points variable (p < .05). The strategic learning orientation seems to exhibit a relatively significant positive relation to the exam points variable (p = .075). I will, thus remove the deep approach variable and attempt to fit a regression model with only two variables, attitude and strategic approach.

After this second iteration, it would seem the strategic approach variable no longer exhibits a statistically significant relation to the exam points variable. I will, thus remove it, and fit a final regression model with attitude as explanatory variable.

Results

pointsmodel <- lm(points ~ attitude, data = learning2014)
summary(pointsmodel)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = points ~ attitude, data = learning2014)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -16.9763  -3.2119   0.4339   4.1534  10.6645 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)  11.6372     1.8303   6.358 1.95e-09 ***
## attitude      3.5255     0.5674   6.214 4.12e-09 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 5.32 on 164 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.1906, Adjusted R-squared:  0.1856 
## F-statistic: 38.61 on 1 and 164 DF,  p-value: 4.119e-09

As the regression model above shows, the exam points -variable is best explained by the variable attitude with a positive correlation (p < .05). The effect of the attitude variable on exam points is approximately 0.35, and the multiple R-squared shows, that less than 5 percent of the variation in exam points is explained by the global attitude towards statistics, which is a typical value for behavioural sciences. As the Figure 2. below illustrates, the errors of the model are normally distributed and not correlated, the size of the errors is not dependent on the explanatory variables and there is no leverage effect of a single observation on the model.

par(mfrow = c(2,2))
plot(pointsmodel, which = c(1,2,5))

Figure 2. The residuals vs. fitted values figure implies no problem with the assumption, that the size of the errors would depend on the explanatory variables. The QQ-plot depicts the errors as quite normally distributed. The residuals-leverate -figure implies no leverage effect of a single observation on the target variable.

Conclusion

Thus it can be concluded, that the global attitude of a participant towards statistics best predicts their success in the course exam of the course “Introduction to Statistics in Social Sciences”, based on this 2014 data. Further data collected on future implementations of the same course can hopefully furhter support this conclusion.

Exercise 4: Clustering and classification

This exercise focuses on clustering and classification methods, such as linear discriminant analysis and k-means clustering. Our research focuses on the crime rate in Boston suburbs.

Data

Our dataset “Boston” is a data frame containing 14 variables and 506 observations on the housing values in the suburbs of Boston. The variables contain factors such as per capita crime rate by town, nitrogen oxides concentration and pupil-teacher ratio by town.

The variables seem normally distributed. Based on the above correlation matrix, there seem to be high negative correlations between proportion of non-retail business acres per town and weighted mean of distances to five Boston employment centres, as well as mean of distances to the employment centers and proportion of owner-occupied units built prior to 1940 as well as nitrogen oxides concentration. Analysis

Standardizing the data

To ease the future interpretation of covariances we will first scale the dataset. After that we will categorize the crime rate variable per quantiles to get “high”, “low” and “middle” rate categories.

crime <- cut(boston_scaled$crim, breaks = bins, include.lowest = TRUE, labels=c("low", "med_low", "med_high", "high"))

Above you can find a summary of the scaled dataset and categorized crime rate. After the scaling of the dataset and categorization of the crime rate variable, we will divide the data set into train (80 %) and test (20 %) sets.

# dividing the train and test sets
n <- nrow(boston_scaled)
ind <- sample(n,  size = n * 0.8)
train <- boston_scaled[ind,]
test <- boston_scaled[-ind,]

Classification

Next, we will create a classification model based on the training data by fitting a linear discriminant analysis. The target variable here is the categorical crime rate with three classes, created above. Hence, we will, among the rest of the variables, try to find variables that best discriminate the three classes of crime rate (“high”, “low” and “medium”).

# 5. fitting an LDA on the train set
lda.fit <- lda(train$crime ~ ., data = train)
lda.fit

# defining the arrow function
lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "red", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}

# target classes as numeric (for plotting purposes)
classes <- as.numeric(train$crime)

# plotting the results (paint both lines to execute)
plot(lda.fit, dimen = 2, col=classes, pch=classes)
lda.arrows(lda.fit, myscale = 1)

Figure 2. The scatter plot of the linear discriminant analysis on crime rate.

Based on our linear discriminant analysis it would seem our crime rate variable is indeed best predicted by index of accessibility to radial highways, a connection we already saw in the correlations.

Prediction

Next we will attempt to predict the classes of the test data based on our model created above.

# 6. 
# saving the crime categories from the test set and then removing the categorical crime variable from the test dataset
correct_classes <- test$crime
test <- dplyr::select(test, -crime)

# predicting the classes with the LDA model on the test data
lda.pred <- predict(lda.fit, newdata = test)

# cross tabulating the results
table(correct = correct_classes, predicted = lda.pred$class)
##           predicted
## correct    low med_low med_high high
##   low       12      13        3    0
##   med_low    4      19        1    0
##   med_high   0      12       19    2
##   high       0       0        0   17

It would seem most of our actual test observations match the model predictions, which validates the model.

The other variables are skew towards the right, apart from the female-male -ratio of secondary education acquisition, which contains two peaks. The correlations seem to be significantly positive between life expectancy and expected years of education, GNI per capita and life expectancy, as well as maternal mortality at birth and adolescent birth rate. Significantly negative correlations can be observed between maternal mortality at birth and female-male ratio in secondary education acquisition, maternal mortality at birth and expected years of education, expected years of education and adolescent birth rate, maternal mortality at birth and life expectancy, as well as adolescent birth rate and life expectancy.

The second principal component would then consist of labour participation rate and percentage of female representation in parliament. Thus, the first principal component contains variables especially related to the “life in years”, so-called, of a country’s population, with factors such as education and birth control having positive correlations with life expectancy and maternal conditions. The second principal component portrays factors related to societal and working life development.

Exercise 6: Analysis of lognitudinal data

Schizophrenia Treatment Alternatives

Data

Our data consist of a lognitudinal sample of BPRS-points (brief psychiatric rating scale) of 40 participants suspected with a schizophrenia diagnosis over an 8 week treatment period, in addition to a pre-measurement week 0, with two alternate treatment conditions. Below the data summaries and figures show how the participants’ test scores decrease over the treatment period in the two treatment conditions, and the so-called tracking phenomenon, or how the individuals’ scores correlate with each other throughout the study.

Analysis

Next we will start formally testing the hypothesized difference between the two treatment conditions. We will start by applying a t-test on the long-form dataset excluding the outlier in treatment condition 2.

# Perform a two-sample t-test
t.test(mean ~ treatment, data = BPRSL8S1, var.equal = TRUE)
## 
##  Two Sample t-test
##

##  -4.232480  7.162085

## mean in group 1 mean in group 2

The t-test summary above confirms no evidence for a between-group difference on a 95 % confidence interval. We will still apply an Analysis of Covariance (ANCOVA) on the dataset controlling the baseline measure of week 0.

# Add the baseline from the original data as a new variable to the summary data
BPRSL8S2 <- BPRSL8S %>%

As the results show, there seems to be clear dependency in the repeated measures of one another. Next we will try out a random intercept model with the two explanatory variables of time and group. This model allows for the linear regression of each rat to differ in intercept from all other rats.

Finally we will fit a random intercept and slope model, which allows for an additional group x time interaction.

From these results we can conclude that the interaction model provides a better fit for the rat growth data, and that the growth rate slopes are significantly higher for rats in group 2 than group 1, but less so comparing group 1 and group 3.

Results

We can conclude our analysis by stating, that the growth rate of rats on diet number 2. was the highest, and thus this diet is the best performing in increasing the rats’ body weight.
